038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"758\" height=\"1348\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/1999-09-03.jpg?w=928&amp;ssl=1 928w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/1999-09-03.jpg?resize=169%2C300&amp;ssl=1 169w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/1999-09-03.jpg?resize=576%2C1024&amp;ssl=1 576w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/1999-09-03.jpg?resize=768%2C1366&amp;ssl=1 768w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/1999-09-03.jpg?resize=864%2C1536&amp;ssl=1 864w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 758px) 100vw, 758px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>2001: </strong>In their last public appearance before the nation changes forever, Bruce and Patti join Brian Kirk and the Jirks on-stage for four songs at Donovan&#8217;s Reef in Sea Bright, New Jersey. (The Jirks are the house band at the club.)</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/VcpMgWrmhUE?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/2Xphm6-kpIA?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/g-cAs0PgBd0?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p><strong>2012:\u00a0</strong>Night Two at Philadelphia&#8217;s Citizens Bank Park was a Labor Day special, opening with an acoustic tour premiere of &#8220;Factory&#8221; as part of a five-song\u00a0<em>Darkness on the Edge of Town\u00a0</em>mini-set. The show stayed intense all the way through, which may be why Bruce omitted setlisted gems like &#8220;Ain&#8217;t Good Enough for You,&#8221; &#8220;Love Train,&#8221; &#8220;(Your Love Keeps Lifting Me) Higher and Higher,&#8221; &#8220;Incident on 57th Street,&#8221; and &#8220;My Love Will Not Let You Down.&#8221; What a show\u00a0<em>that</em> would have been!</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/9BaJ4KRkFcA?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtu